        "Model 2: Random Forest Model"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "my_z33L1W3sd"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Note: A Random Forest is used here because it doesn't assume relationships are straight lines. It can easily learn complex patterns, like how a 50% discount might be fine for high-volume technology items but completely catastrophic for low-volume furniture."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "qnmrkaRfXnf_"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Part 1: Model Training & Evaluation Metrics Table\n",
        "\n",
        "This block initializes the Random Forest engine. Using the exact same one-hot encoded variables (X_train, X_test) and random_state=42 ensures that the train/test split is identical to Model 1, making our model's metrics comparison completely fair. It fits the ensemble trees and outputs the second performance metrics table."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "g6RArYQ2YFxY"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
        "from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor\n",
        "from sklearn.metrics import r2_score, mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error\n",
        "\n",
        "# --- 1. ENCODING & REUSING SPLITS ---\n",
        "categorical_features = ['Ship_Mode', 'Segment', 'Region', 'Category']\n",
        "numerical_features = ['Quantity', 'Discount']\n",
        "\n",
        "X_encoded = pd.get_dummies(df[categorical_features + numerical_features], drop_first=True)\n",
        "y_sales = df['Sales']\n",
        "y_profit = df['Profit']\n",
        "model_features = X_encoded.columns\n",
        "\n",
        "X_train_s, X_test_s, y_train_s, y_test_s = train_test_split(X_encoded, y_sales, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)\n",
        "X_train_p, X_test_p, y_train_p, y_test_p = train_test_split(X_encoded, y_profit, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)\n",
        "\n",
        "# --- 2. REGULARIZED RANDOM FOREST REGRESSOR (TUNED TO FIX OVERFITTING) ---\n",
        "# We restrict max_depth and set min_samples_leaf to force the trees to generalize\n",
        "rf_model_sales = RandomForestRegressor(\n",
        "    n_estimators=150,\n",
        "    max_depth=6,\n",
        "    min_samples_leaf=5,\n",
        "    random_state=42,\n",
        "    n_jobs=-1\n",
        ")\n",
        "rf_model_sales.fit(X_train_s, y_train_s)\n",
        "\n",
        "rf_model_profit = RandomForestRegressor(\n",
        "    n_estimators=150,\n",
        "    max_depth=6,\n",
        "    min_samples_leaf=5,\n",
        "    random_state=42,\n",
        "    n_jobs=-1\n",
        ")\n",
        "rf_model_profit.fit(X_train_p, y_train_p)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Generate new predictions\n",
        "rf_sales_preds = rf_model_sales.predict(X_test_s)\n",
        "rf_profit_preds = rf_model_profit.predict(X_test_p)\n",
        "\n",
        "# --- 3. CALCULATE TUNED METRICS ---\n",
        "rf_metrics_report = pd.DataFrame({\n",
        "    'Metric': ['R-Squared', 'MSE', 'RMSE', 'MAE'],\n",
        "    'Sales Forecast Model (RF)': [\n",
        "        r2_score(y_test_s, rf_sales_preds),\n",
        "        mean_squared_error(y_test_s, rf_sales_preds),\n",
        "        np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test_s, rf_sales_preds)),\n",
        "        mean_absolute_error(y_test_s, rf_sales_preds)\n",
        "    ],\n",
        "    'Profit Forecast Model (RF)': [\n",
        "        r2_score(y_test_p, rf_profit_preds),\n",
        "        mean_squared_error(y_test_p, rf_profit_preds),\n",
        "        np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test_p, rf_profit_preds)),\n",
        "        mean_absolute_error(y_test_p, rf_profit_preds)\n",
        "    ]\n",
        "})\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"=== Model 2: Optimized Random Forest Regressor ===\")\n",
        "display(rf_metrics_report)"
      ],
